EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This document establishes a standardized dual-definition framework for terminology frequently deployed by Technology Executives, AI Founders, Venture Futurists, and Podcast-Based Economists (hereafter collectively referred to as “Tech Sages”). The objective is to reconcile discrepancies between Oxford Dictionary definitions (Reality Layer) and Tech Sage definitions (Funding Layer).

The Committee has determined that many critical terms no longer share semantic continuity across these layers, resulting in widespread confusion, speculative hiring freezes, and PowerPoint-induced labor market volatility. This dictionary therefore provides an official translation framework to enable policymakers, workers, and confused relatives to interpret Tech Sage statements without experiencing semantic whiplash.

⸻

METHODOLOGY

Terms were collected from:
	•	Podcast transcripts
	•	Conference keynote presentations
	•	Venture capital pitch decks
	•	Tweets containing the phrase “we’re not talking about this enough”
	•	Panels titled “The Future of Everything”
	•	Statements beginning with “People don’t realize…”

Each term was analyzed using the Semantic Divergence Index (SDI), defined as:

SDI = (Amount of Funding Raised Using the Word) ÷ (Amount the Speaker Can Actually Define It)

Terms with SDI > 10 were classified as Category A: Critical Buzzwords and included in this document.

